        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3252138282" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1610063961985748850">3.5*<br/><br/>Librarians, vampires - you’d think this would be my perfect cup of light entertainment. Well...not exactly. <br/><br/>The general premise interested me, and ultimately, I did not mind B and Gio, even giving them plenty of time for character and relation building. The slowness of the narration didn’t bother me since I was curious to see how it would all develop, including some compelling secondary characters and references to the Italy of the 15th century. Add to this Hunter’s great idea of giving vamp</span>
  <span id="freeText1610063961985748850" style="display:none">3.5*<br /><br />Librarians, vampires - you’d think this would be my perfect cup of light entertainment. Well...not exactly. <br /><br />The general premise interested me, and ultimately, I did not mind B and Gio, even giving them plenty of time for character and relation building. The slowness of the narration didn’t bother me since I was curious to see how it would all develop, including some compelling secondary characters and references to the Italy of the 15th century. Add to this Hunter’s great idea of giving vampires elemental affinities, and I was hooked.<br /><br />However, even with all this potential, the story fell flat somehow. Too much telling instead of showing, which hindered the flow of the narration, as did all those time lapses between some chapters. Writing style could have done with a bit more editing (for instance, quite a few repetitions). Not enough development of those great side protagonists, or indeed the fertile historical element. And a ‘baddie’ that wasn’t strong enough. It’s hard to pinpoint, and it is annoying the hell out of me since I was expecting so much more. <br /><br />Will I carry on? Not sure. Part of me still wants to see if the author gets the mixture right in the next instalment.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1610063961985748850" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


